Arrays.fill() is a method in java.util.Arrays class which assigns a specified value to each element of an entire array or a specified range within the specified array.

-> Filling an Entire Array with a Value
Let us start with a simple example where we fill the complete array with a single value.

import java.util.Arrays;
​
public class GFG { 
    public static void main(String[] args) {
      
        // Create an array of 5 integers
        int[] arr = new int[5];
​
        // Fill the entire array with the value 2
        Arrays.fill(arr, 2);
​
        System.out.println("" + Arrays.toString(arr));
    }
}

Output
[2, 2, 2, 2, 2]
Explanation:
• The array is initially filled with default values (0).
• Arrays.fill(arr, 2) replaces every element with 2.
• Arrays.toString() is used to print the array in readable format.

-> Syntax of Arrays.fill() method
  public static void fill(int[] a, int val)
  public static void fill(int[] a, int fromIndex, int toIndex, int val)

Parameters:
• a: Array to be filled.
• val: Value to assign to each element of the array.
• fromIndex: Starting index (inclusive) for filling.
• toIndex: Ending index (exclusive) for filling.

Return Type: It does not return any value, but modifies the array directly.

Time Complexity:
• O(n) : when filling the entire array (where n is array length)
• O(toIndex − fromIndex) : when filling a specific range

Exceptions:
• IllegalArgumentException: Thrown if fromIndex > toIndex
• ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException: Thrown if fromIndex < 0 or toIndex > array length

-> Examples of Arrays.fill() in Java
1. Fill a Specific Range in an Array
In this example, only a portion of the array is filled with a new value while the remaining elements stay unchanged.
import java.util.Arrays;
​
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        
      int arr[] = {2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 2,};
​
        // Fill from index 1 to index 4
        Arrays.fill(arr, 1, 4, 5);
   
        System.out.println(Arrays.toString(arr));
    }
}

Output
[2, 5, 5, 5, 2, 2, 2]
Explanation:
• Index 1 to 3 are filled with 5
• Index 4 is excluded
• Other elements remain unchanged

2. Fill a 2D Array with a Specific Value
Arrays.fill() works on one-dimensional arrays, so for multi-dimensional arrays, we fill each row separately.

import java.util.Arrays;
​
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        
      int [][]arr = new int[2][2];
​
        // Fill each row with 5 
        for (int[] r : arr)
            Arrays.fill(r, 5);
   
        System.out.println(Arrays.deepToString(arr));
    }
}

Output
[[5, 5], [5, 5]]
Explanation:
• Each row is a 1D array
• Arrays.fill() is applied to every row using a for-each loop
• Arrays.deepToString() is used for printing multi-dimensional arrays

3. Fill a 3D Array with a Specific Value
In this example, again we will use Arrays.fill() method to fill each element of a 3D array with a specific value i.e. 2. Here, we will be using Nested loops to fill each row and column in the 3D array.
import java.util.Arrays;
​
class GFG {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        
      int[][][] arr = new int[2][2][2];
​
        // Fill each row with 2 
        for (int[][] r : arr) {
            for (int[] c : r) {
                Arrays.fill(c, 2);
            }
        }
​
        System.out.println(Arrays.deepToString(arr));
    }
}

Output
[[[2, 2], [2, 2]], [[2, 2], [2, 2]]]
Explanation:

Each level of loop accesses deeper dimensions
Arrays.fill() fills the innermost 1D arrays
Works efficiently for initializing multi-dimensional arrays
